   803	### 7. Usage Workflows Connecting Templates, Skills, Completions, And Generated Workspaces
   804	
   805	Normative claims:
   806	
   807	- Rhei plans are shared artifacts with distinct role mandates: plan writer
   808	  structures work, plan worker executes, reviewer inspects, human operator
   809	  unblocks human gates and may override.
   810	- The state machine is the coordination protocol: it defines states,
   811	  transitions, actors, and handoffs. Agents communicate through plan state and
   812	  artifacts.
   813	- Manual-worker and `rhei run` execution are mutually exclusive per task:
   814	  workers use `rhei next`, `rhei transition`, and `rhei complete`; spawned
   815	  agents under `rhei run` leave state mutation to the orchestrator.
   816	- `human-review` and other gating states are human-only and must not be
   817	  bypassed by automated workflows.
   818	- Directory workspaces are the recommended generated shape for highly
   819	  concurrent or living workflows because task files can be appended/merged
   820	  independently.
   821	- Living workspace expansion should append verification/fix tasks only after
   822	  concrete artifacts justify them; speculative follow-up tasks should not be
   823	  present up front.
   824	- Program states and CI/CD plans are valid generated workflow examples when
   825	  deterministic commands, exit codes, and human gates are encoded in the state
   826	  machine.
   827	- The plan file/workspace is the single source of truth for resumability,
   828	  auditability, human legibility, and composability.
   829	
