     1	# Rhei Templates Specification
     2	
     3	This document specifies **Rhei Templates** — parameterized, reusable plan+state-machine bundles that can be instantiated with concrete inputs to produce ready-to-execute workspaces.
     4	
     5	## Motivation
     6	
     7	Rhei plans and state machines today are authored from scratch or copied manually. Common patterns — code review loops, release checklists, onboarding workflows — are recreated each time. Templates let users capture a proven workflow once and instantiate it with project-specific inputs, removing boilerplate and enforcing consistency.
     8	
     9	## Concepts
    10	
    11	A **template** is a directory containing:
    12	
    13	1. A **manifest** (`template.yaml`) declaring the template's name, description, and typed input parameters.
    14	2. A **state machine** (`states.yaml`) — optional; when absent, instantiation and validation fall back to the built-in `rhei` default.
    15	3. A **plan skeleton** — either a single-file plan (`plan.rhei.md`) or a directory-workspace layout (`index.rhei.md` + `tasks/`).
    16	4. **Additional files** — any non-manifest files bundled with the template. Text files are rendered with a restricted MiniJinja template environment; binary files are copied verbatim into the output.
    17	
    18	Materialized template files may contain **instantiation templates** (`{{ ... }}`, `{% ... %}`) that are resolved at instantiation time from user-supplied inputs. These are distinct from the single-brace **runtime variables** (`{name}`) defined by the state-machine and plan specifications. Rendering is ordered: first resolve MiniJinja templates across template files during `rhei instantiate`, then let later `rhei` commands resolve runtime `{...}` variables against the instantiated workspace. The manifest (`template.yaml`) is parsed before rendering and is never itself templated.
    19	
    20	## Template Discovery
    21	
    22	Templates are resolved in order, first match wins:
    23	
    24	| Priority | Location | Scope |
    25	|----------|----------|-------|
    26	| 1 | `<project>/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/` | Project-local |
    27	| 2 | `~/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/` | User-global |
    28	
    29	The `<name>` is the directory name and serves as the template identifier used in CLI commands.
    30	
    31	Discovery errors are handled per command:
    32	
    33	- `rhei templates` skips unreadable or invalid template directories and prints a warning naming the skipped path.
    34	- `rhei instantiate <name>` fails if the matched template directory is unreadable or invalid.
    35	- `rhei instantiate <path>` fails if the explicit template path is unreadable or invalid.
    36	
    37	## Directory Layout
    38	
    39	```
    40	<name>/
    41	├── template.yaml          # Manifest (required)
    42	├── states.yaml            # State machine (optional)
    43	├── settings.json          # Template-shipped project settings (optional)
    44	├── plan.rhei.md           # Single-file plan skeleton
    45	│   ── OR ──
    46	├── index.rhei.md          # Directory-workspace index skeleton
    47	├── tasks/                 # Directory-workspace task skeletons
    48	│   ├── 01-step.md
    49	│   └── ...
    50	└── ...                    # Additional files (text rendered; binary copied)
    51	```
    52	
    53	A template must contain exactly one plan entry point: either `plan.rhei.md` (single-file) or `index.rhei.md` (directory workspace). Containing both is an error.
    54	
    55	## Manifest Schema (`template.yaml`)
    56	
    57	```yaml
    58	name: <identifier>             # Template identifier (must match directory name)
    59	version: <yaml-scalar>         # Template version (informational; displayed by `rhei templates`;
    60	                               #   no semantic-version validation in v1)
    61	description: <string>          # One-line human-readable summary
    62	
    63	inputs:
    64	  - name: <identifier>        # Variable name, referenced as {{name}} in skeletons
    65	    description: <string>      # What this input controls
    66	    type: <string|number|boolean|path|array|object>  # Value type (default: string)
    67	    required: <boolean>        # Whether the input must be supplied (default: true)
    68	    default: <value>           # Default value (makes the input optional; mutually
    69	                               #   exclusive with required: true)
    70	    positional: <integer>       # Optional 1-based positional CLI slot for short
    71	                               #   `rhei instantiate <template> <value>` input
    72	    validate: <regex>          # Optional regex the value must match
    73	    items:                     # Required for `type: array`
    74	      type: <...>
    75	      ...
    76	    properties:                # Optional for `type: object`
    77	      <property-name>:
    78	        type: <...>
    79	        required: <boolean>
    80	        default: <value>
    81	        ...
    82	```
    83	
    84	### Validation Rules
    85	
    86	- `name` must match the enclosing directory name.
    87	- `inputs[].name` values must be unique within the manifest.
    88	- `version` is informational metadata. In v1 it may be any YAML scalar and is not semantically validated.
    89	- An input with `required: true` (the default) must not declare a `default`.
    90	- An input with a `default` is implicitly `required: false`.
    91	- An input with `required: false` and no `default` resolves to the empty string when not supplied by the user. Templates are pure text substitution in v1, so authors should tolerate that empty string directly or prefer declaring a `default`.
    92	- `positional`, when present, must be a positive integer. Positional indexes must be unique within a manifest and contiguous starting at `1`.
    93	- `type: array` inputs must declare `items`.
    94	- `type: object` inputs may declare `properties`. Properties are required by default unless they declare either `required: false` or a `default`.
    95	- `validate` is only valid on scalar input types (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, `path`).
    96	- Optional inputs with no `default` resolve to type-shaped empty values:
    97	  - `string`, `path` → `""`
    98	  - `number`, `boolean` → `null`
    99	  - `array` → `[]`
   100	  - `object` → `{}`
   101	- For `type: array` and `type: object`, positional values, `KEY=VALUE`, `--set KEY=...`, and `--set-file KEY=...` values are parsed as YAML/JSON snippets before validation.
   102	- `type: path` values are rendered exactly as supplied by the user or manifest `default`; instantiation does not rewrite them to absolute paths. Relative `path` values are interpreted relative to the instantiating process `cwd` only when the CLI itself must resolve that path for its own file operations. The exception is an omitted optional `path` input with no `default`, which resolves to the empty string.
   103	- `validate`, when present, is a Rust `regex`-crate pattern applied to the string representation of the resolved scalar value and anchored to the entire rendered value.
   104	
   105	## Template-Shipped Settings
   106	
   107	A template may bundle a `settings.json` file alongside `template.yaml` to
   108	declare project-scoped settings that the instantiated workspace should start
   109	with — most commonly, the MCP server and skill profiles the state machine
   110	references.
   111	
   112	The file uses the standard project settings schema documented in
   113	[Agents Specification — Global and Project Settings](rhei-agents.spec.md#global-and-project-settings).
   114	It is treated as a text template file: instantiation variables (`{{name}}`)
   115	are resolved at instantiation time so a template can parameterize
   116	workspace-specific values (workspace ids, paths, hostnames) without exposing
   117	host secrets.
   118	
   119	On instantiation the rendered file is written to `.rhei/settings.json` in the
   120	output tree, where `rhei run` and `rhei validate` automatically pick it up and
   121	compose it over the user's global `~/.config/rhei/settings.json`.
   122	
   123	Example:
   124	
   125	```json
   126	// settings.json inside the template
   127	{
   128	  "mcp_servers": {
   129	    "linear": {
   130	      "command": ["npx", "-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-linear"],
   131	      "env": { "LINEAR_WORKSPACE": "{{linear_workspace_id}}" }
   132	    }
   133	  },
   134	  "skills": {
   135	    "review-checklist": { "path": ".rhei/skills/review-checklist" }
   136	  },
   137	  "defaults": {
   138	    "mcp_servers": ["linear"]
   139	  }
   140	}
   141	```
   142	
   143	With the matching manifest input:
   144	
   145	```yaml
   146	# template.yaml
   147	inputs:
   148	  - name: linear_workspace_id
   149	    description: Linear workspace id used by the Linear MCP server
   150	    type: string
   151	    required: true
   152	```
   153	
   154	Rules:
   155	
   156	- `settings.json` must be a UTF-8 JSON file. Instantiation fails if parsing
   157	  the rendered file fails.
   158	- References to host secrets use the settings file's standard `${VAR}`
   159	  expansion — **not** template variables — so secrets are resolved at
   160	  `rhei run` time on the user's machine, not baked into the output.
   161	- A template that references MCP or skill ids in its `states.yaml` must
   162	  declare matching registry entries either in its bundled `settings.json`
   163	  or expect the user to provide them in their global settings. `rhei
   164	  validate` (step 6 above) surfaces any remaining dangling references as
   165	  errors.
   166	- Users may edit `.rhei/settings.json` after instantiation to replace
   167	  template-declared entries, add project-specific overrides, or clear the
   168	  `defaults` lists.
   169	
   170	## Instantiation Template Syntax
   171	
   172	Instantiation rendering uses a restricted [MiniJinja](https://github.com/mitsuhiko/minijinja)-style environment. This is intentionally distinct from the single-brace runtime variables (`{task_id}`, `{visit_count}`, etc.) that later `rhei` commands resolve at execution time.
   173	
   174	Supported constructs in v1:
   175	
   176	- `{{ expr }}` for interpolation
   177	- `{% for item in items %}` ... `{% endfor %}` for loops
   178	- `{% if cond %}` ... `{% else %}` ... `{% endif %}` for conditionals
   179	- `{% raw %}` ... `{% endraw %}` for literal template syntax
   180	- `|slug` filter for filesystem-safe slugs
   181	
   182	The renderer is **strict**:
   183	
   184	- Referencing an undefined variable or missing object property is an error.
   185	- `template.yaml` is parsed before rendering and is never templated.
   186	- The environment does not load external templates; includes/imports are unavailable.
   187	
   188	### Resolution Rules
   189	
   190	- Instantiation templates are resolved **at instantiation time**, producing a concrete plan with no remaining `{{...}}` / `{% ... %}` markers.
   191	- Runtime variables (`{...}`) pass through instantiation untouched — they remain in the output for `rhei next` to resolve later.
   192	- An unresolved `{{name}}` or missing `foo.bar` property is an **error** (fail-closed), unlike runtime variables which fail-open. This catches typos early.
   193	- Instantiation always happens before any runtime `{...}` substitution from bundled or default state machines.
   194	- Instantiation variables can appear in any **text** file that is materialized into the output tree. `template.yaml` is parsed before rendering, is excluded from output, and must not rely on `{{...}}` substitution.
   195	- A file is considered text if it contains no null bytes in its first 8 KiB; all other files are binary.
   196	- Text template files must decode as UTF-8. If a file is classified as text but cannot be decoded as UTF-8, instantiation fails with a file-read error.
   197	- Binary files (images, compiled artifacts) are copied without instantiation-variable resolution or UTF-8 decoding.
   198	
   199	### Escaping
   200	
   201	To emit a literal `{{` or `{%`, prefer MiniJinja raw blocks:
   202	
   203	```jinja
   204	{% raw %}{{target.slug}}{% endraw %}
   205	```
   206	
   207	For backward compatibility, `\{{` also emits a literal `{{` and the backslash is consumed during instantiation.
   208	
   209	## CLI Commands
   210	
   211	### `rhei instantiate`
   212	
   213	Create a concrete plan workspace from a template.
   214	
   215	```
   216	rhei instantiate <template> [input ...] [options]
   217	
   218	Arguments:
   219	  <template>                   Template name or path to a template directory
   220	  [input ...]                  Positional input values or key=value assignments
   221	
   222	Options:
   223	  --set <key>=<value>          Set an input value (repeatable)
   224	  --set-file <key>=<path>      Set an input value from file contents (repeatable)
   225	  --values <file>              Load input values from a YAML or JSON file (repeatable;
   226	                                 later files, then input args / --set, then --set-file
   227	                                 override earlier values)
   228	  --output <path>              Output directory (default: ./<template-name>/ where
   229	                                 <template-name> is the directory basename of the
   230	                                 resolved template)
   231	  --execute                    Instantiate and immediately begin execution
   232	  --dry-run                    Show what would be generated without writing files
   233	  --keep-on-error              Keep output directory on validation failure
   234	  --list-inputs                Print the template's input schema and exit
   235	```
   236	
   237	#### Input UX
   238	
   239	`rhei instantiate` supports three equivalent ways to provide simple template
   240	inputs:
   241	
   242	```bash
   243	rhei instantiate spec-review docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md
   244	rhei instantiate code-review target=src/auth review_passes=3
   245	rhei instantiate code-review --set target=src/auth --set review_passes=3
   246	```
   247	
   248	`--set` remains the explicit, script-safe form. Bare `KEY=VALUE` arguments are
   249	short syntax for `--set KEY=VALUE`. Bare values without `=` are positional input
   250	values.
   251	
   252	A template may opt into positional input values by declaring `positional` on
   253	one or more inputs:
   254	
   255	```yaml
   256	inputs:
   257	  - name: spec
   258	    description: Path to the specification file to review
   259	    type: path
   260	    positional: 1
   261	
   262	  - name: criteria
   263	    description: Additional things to look for during review
   264	    type: string
   265	    required: false
   266	    default: ""
   267	```
   268	
   269	With that manifest, these commands are equivalent:
   270	
   271	```bash
   272	rhei instantiate spec-review docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md
   273	rhei instantiate spec-review spec=docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md
   274	rhei instantiate spec-review --set spec=docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md
   275	```
   276	
   277	For backward-compatible convenience, if a template declares exactly one
   278	required input and no `positional` fields, one bare input value maps to that
   279	required input. Templates with zero required inputs, multiple required inputs,
   280	or multiple bare input values must declare `positional` fields or use explicit
   281	`KEY=VALUE` / `--set` input.
   282	
   283	Input arguments are parsed as follows:
   284	
   285	- `KEY=VALUE` is an assignment when `KEY` is a valid input identifier. The key
   286	  must name a declared template input.
   287	- A value containing `=` is treated as a positional value when the text before
   288	  the first `=` is not a valid input identifier. This keeps path-like values
   289	  containing `=` usable.
   290	- A positional value is assigned to the input with the matching `positional`
   291	  index. When using the single-required-input fallback, it is assigned to that
   292	  required input.
   293	- Supplying the same input more than once is allowed. Later values from the
   294	  same precedence group override earlier values.
   295	- If both a positional value and an explicit assignment set the same input, the
   296	  explicit assignment wins.
   297	- `--set-file KEY=PATH` remains the file-content form and has higher precedence
   298	  than positional values, `KEY=VALUE`, and `--set`.
   299	
   300	#### Behavior
   301	
   302	1. **Locate template.** Resolve `<template>` through the discovery chain unless it is already a filesystem path. Direct paths include absolute paths, relative paths containing `/`, and dot-prefixed relative paths such as `./my-template` or `../templates/review`.
   303	2. **Load manifest.** Parse `template.yaml`, validate schema.
   304	3. **Collect inputs.** Resolve inputs using this precedence order: manifest defaults < `--values` files from left to right < positional input values < `KEY=VALUE` input arguments and `--set` flags from left to right < `--set-file` flags from left to right. Error on missing required inputs, unknown input names, ambiguous positional values, or duplicate `positional` declarations. Validate types and `validate` patterns. For `array` / `object` inputs, positional values, `KEY=VALUE`, `--set`, and `--set-file` values are parsed as YAML/JSON snippets before validation.
   305	4. **Render templates.** Walk all materialized text files in the template directory and render them through the restricted MiniJinja environment. `template.yaml` is parsed before this step and is never rendered into the output. Error on any unresolved instantiation template reference.
   306	5. **Write output.** In normal mode, copy the resolved tree to `--output`. `--output` must not already exist; instantiation fails rather than merging into or overwriting an existing path. In `--dry-run` mode, the CLI skips the output-path existence check, materializes into a temporary scratch directory instead of `--output`, validates that scratch output, and reports what would have been written. Preserve directory structure and file permissions. Hidden files and directories (names starting with `.`) and `template.yaml` itself are excluded from the output. A root-level `settings.json` in the template is moved to `.rhei/settings.json` under the output root; all other files preserve their template-relative paths.
   307	6. **Validate.** Run `rhei validate` on the instantiated plan. If the output root contains `states.yaml`, treat that file as the state machine for validation; otherwise fall back to the built-in default. Validation composes the merged settings (global, then output-root `.rhei/settings.json`) and resolves every `agent`, `model`, `mcp_servers`, and `skills` reference declared in the state machine. Warnings are printed; errors abort (output directory is removed on error unless `--keep-on-error` is passed).
   308	7. **Print summary.** After successful validation, print a human-readable instantiation summary with the output path, task/state counts, instantiated output tree, rendered task tree, the last few rendered task definitions in source order, and a stop-point explanation. For normal instantiation without `--execute`, the stop point is the next ready task and the reason is that execution has not started.
   309	8. **Print invocation.** Print a shell-safe `rhei instantiate ... --output <path>` command that shows how to instantiate the same template and input values again. The printed command uses the resolved output path, so shell expressions such as `$(date ...)` appear as the concrete path value seen by the CLI.
   310	9. **Execute (optional).** When `--execute` is passed, invoke `rhei run <output>` after successful validation. `rhei run` uses the instantiated output's root `states.yaml` by default when present; otherwise it falls back to the built-in default.
   311	
   312	#### Instantiation Summary Output
   313	
   314	After successful validation, `rhei instantiate` prints a compact report before
   315	the reproducible invocation. The report is intended to be useful for both
   316	humans and agent-orchestrator logs: it shows what was created, which tasks are
   317	present, the most recent task definitions, and why instantiation stopped.
   318	
   319	The summary uses these headings in order:
   320	
   321	```text
   322	=== Instantiation Summary ===
   323	Output: <output-path>
   324	Tasks: <count>
   325	States: <state=count[, ...]>
   326	
   327	Files:
   328	  <output-path>/
   329	  ...
   330	
   331	Task tree:
   332	  - Task <id>: <title> [<state>]
   333	  ...
   334	
   335	Recent task definitions:
   336	--- Task <id>: <title> [<state>] ---
   337	### Task <id>: <title>
   338	**State:** <state>
   339	...
   340	
   341	Stopped:
   342	  <stop reason>
   343	```
   344	
   345	`Files` prints the full instantiated output tree, including hidden files that
   346	were generated by instantiation such as `.rhei/settings.json`. The root line
   347	uses the user-requested `--output` path. In `--dry-run`, this is still the
   348	requested path even though the rendered files live in a temporary scratch
   349	directory and are discarded after validation.
   350	
   351	`Task tree` prints every rendered task in source order, preserving hierarchy by
   352	indentation. Each line includes the canonical task kind, task id, title, and
   353	current state.
   354	
   355	`Recent task definitions` prints up to the last five rendered task definitions
   356	in source order. Each definition reconstructs the task heading, `**State:**`,
   357	`**Prior:**` when present, `**Assignee:**` when present, and the task body. It
   358	does not inline child task definitions under a parent; child tasks appear as
   359	their own recent definitions when they are among the last five tasks.
   360	
   361	`Stopped` explains the current hand-off point:
   362	
   363	- In `--dry-run`, the reason says rendering and validation succeeded but no
   364	  files were written to the requested output path.
   365	- If all tasks are terminal, the reason says the plan is already complete.
   366	- If one or more tasks are in a gating state, the reason lists the first few
   367	  human-gated tasks.
   368	- If at least one task is ready, the reason names the next ready task and shows
   369	  `rhei run <output>` and `rhei next <output>` follow-up commands.
   370	- If no task is ready because prerequisites are incomplete, the reason lists
   371	  the first few blocked tasks.
   372	- If none of the above applies, the reason says validation succeeded but no
   373	  claimable task was found.
   374	
   375	#### Exit Codes
   376	
   377	| Code | Meaning |
   378	|------|---------|
   379	| 0 | Success |
   380	| 1 | Any instantiation error, including template lookup failure, missing or invalid inputs, unresolved instantiation variables, output-path conflicts, validation failure, or `--execute` runtime failure surfaced by the CLI |
   381	
   382	### `rhei templates`
   383	
   384	List available templates.
   385	
   386	```
   387	rhei templates [options]
   388	
   389	Options:
   390	  --json                       Output as JSON
   391	  --source <project|user|all>  Filter by source (default: all)
   392	```
   393	
   394	Prints a table of discovered templates with name, version, description, source path, and required input count.
   395	
   396	When discovery encounters an invalid template directory, `rhei templates` skips it and prints a warning instead of failing the entire listing.
   397	
   398	## Example
   399	
   400	### Template: `code-review`
   401	
   402	```
   403	~/.agents/rhei/templates/code-review/
   404	├── template.yaml
   405	├── states.yaml
   406	├── index.rhei.md
   407	├── tasks/
   408	│   └── 01-review.md
   409	└── workflow.sh
   410	```
   411	
   412	#### `template.yaml`
   413	
   414	```yaml
   415	name: code-review
   416	version: 1.0.0
   417	description: Multi-pass code review with fix loop
   418	
   419	inputs:
   420	  - name: target
   421	    description: File or directory to review
   422	    type: path
   423	    positional: 1
   424	
   425	  - name: review_passes
   426	    description: Number of review iterations
   427	    type: number
   428	    default: 2
   429	
   430	  - name: model
   431	    description: Model to use for review
   432	    default: claude
   433	```
   434	
   435	#### `index.rhei.md`
   436	
   437	```markdown
   438	# Rhei: Code Review — {{target}}
   439	**States:** code-review
   440	
   441	## Overview
   442	Automated {{review_passes}}-pass review of `{{target}}` using {{model}}.
   443	```
   444	
   445	#### `tasks/01-review.md`
   446	
   447	```markdown
   448	### Task review: Review {{target}}
   449	**State:** review
   450	
   451	Review `{{target}}` for correctness, style, and security issues.
   452	Write findings to `{output.review-notes.path}`.
   453	```
   454	
   455	#### `states.yaml`
   456	
   457	```yaml
   458	name: code-review
   459	version: 1.0.0
   460	
   461	states:
   462	  review:
   463	    description: Review pass
   464	    instructions: |
   465	      Review pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   466	      Focus on `{{target}}`.
   467	      Write findings to `{output.review-notes.path}`.
   468	    visits: {{review_passes}}
   469	    outputs:
   470	      - name: review-notes
   471	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   472	
   473	  fix:
   474	    description: Fix findings from review
   475	    instructions: |
   476	      Fix pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   477	      Read `{input.review-notes.path}` and apply fixes to `{{target}}`.
   478	      Write a summary of changes to `{output.fix-summary.path}`.
   479	    visits: {{review_passes}}
   480	    inputs:
   481	      - name: review-notes
   482	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   483	    outputs:
   484	      - name: fix-summary
   485	        path: runtime/fixes/task-{task_id}-fix-{visit_count}.md
   486	
   487	  completed:
   488	    description: Review and fixes complete.
   489	    final: true
   490	
   491	  cancelled:
   492	    description: Review cancelled.
   493	    final: true
   494	
   495	transitions:
   496	  - from: review
   497	    to: fix
   498	    description: Review pass done, apply fixes.
   499	  - from: fix
   500	    to: review
   501	    condition: visitCount < visits
   502	    description: Return for another review pass.
   503	  - from: fix
   504	    to: completed
   505	    condition: visitCount >= visits
   506	    description: All passes complete.
   507	  - from: "*"
   508	    to: cancelled
   509	    description: Cancel from any state.
   510	
   511	profiles:
   512	  default:
   513	    initial: review
   514	    allowed: [review, fix, completed, cancelled]
   515	
   516	node_policy:
   517	  root: default
   518	  default: default
   519	```
   520	
   521	### Instantiation
   522	
   523	```bash
   524	rhei instantiate code-review src/auth/ \
   525	  review_passes=3 \
   526	  --output ./reviews/auth-review/
   527	
   528	# Or instantiate and run immediately:
   529	rhei instantiate code-review src/auth/ --execute
   530	```
   531	
   532	### Resulting Output (`./reviews/auth-review/`)
   533	
   534	```markdown
   535	# index.rhei.md
   536	# Rhei: Code Review — src/auth/
   537	**States:** code-review
   538	
   539	## Overview
   540	Automated 3-pass review of `src/auth/` using claude.
   541	```
   542	
   543	```yaml
   544	# states.yaml (instantiation variables resolved; path text preserved as authored input)
   545	name: code-review
   546	states:
   547	  review:
   548	    instructions: |
   549	      Review pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   550	      Focus on `src/auth/`.
   551	    visits: 3
   552	    ...
   553	```
   554	
   555	All `{{...}}` are resolved during instantiation. All `{...}` remain for runtime.
   556	
   557	## Interaction with Existing Features
   558	
   559	| Feature | Interaction |
   560	|---------|-------------|
   561	| **Runtime variables** (`{task_id}`, etc.) | Pass through instantiation untouched. Resolved later by `rhei next`. |
   562	| **State machines** | A template may bundle its own `states.yaml` at the output root. If present, `rhei instantiate`, `rhei validate`, `rhei run`, `rhei next`, and related commands that operate on the instantiated workspace use that sibling/root `states.yaml` by default when `--state-machine` is not supplied; otherwise they fall back to the built-in default. When the rendered plan declares `**States:** <name>`, that declaration participates in lookup: the auto-discovered `states.yaml` is the active configuration and its `name` must match `<name>`. `--state-machine <path>` overrides the auto-discovered file. Templates that rely on non-default state names should therefore bundle `states.yaml`. |
   563	| **Directory workspaces** | Templates can produce directory workspaces. The `tasks/` directory and `index.rhei.md` are resolved like any other template file. |
   564	| **`rhei validate`** | Runs automatically post-instantiation. Template authors can validate their templates with `rhei instantiate --dry-run`. |
   565	| **Program states** | Program states (`program` field) work in templates. Instantiation variables resolve in `program` strings, `program.command` arrays, `program.env` values, and `program.working_directory`. Runtime variables in those fields pass through to `rhei run`. |
   566	| **Skills** | The `rhei-plan-worker` skill works on instantiated plans identically to hand-authored plans. No skill changes required. |
   567	| **`install-skills`** | Unchanged. Templates are orthogonal to skill installation. |
   568	
   569	## Grammar Extension
   570	
   571	The `rhei_document` and `workspace_index` productions are unchanged. Templates are a pre-processing layer that produces valid Rhei documents — the parser never sees `{{...}}` syntax.
   572	
   573	No changes to the Rhei plan grammar are required.
   574	
   575	## Manifest Fields
   576	
   577	`template.yaml` is a YAML mapping parsed by field name, not by key order. The following schema is normative:
   578	
   579	| Field | Type | Required | Notes |
   580	|-------|------|----------|-------|
   581	| `name` | string | Yes | Must match the enclosing template directory name and the identifier rules described above. |
   582	| `version` | YAML scalar | Yes | Informational metadata only in v1. |
   583	| `description` | string | Yes | Must be non-empty after trimming. |
   584	| `inputs` | sequence of mappings | No | Defaults to an empty list when omitted. |
   585	
   586	Each `inputs[]` entry is a YAML mapping with these fields:
   587	
   588	| Field | Type | Required | Notes |
   589	|-------|------|----------|-------|
   590	| `name` | string | Yes | Unique within the manifest; referenced as `{{name}}` in instantiation variables. |
   591	| `description` | string | Yes | Must be non-empty after trimming. |
   592	| `type` | `string` \| `number` \| `boolean` \| `path` \| `array` \| `object` | No | Defaults to `string`. |
   593	| `required` | boolean | No | Defaults to `true` unless a `default` is present. |
   594	| `default` | YAML value | No | Must be compatible with `type`; mutually exclusive with `required: true`. |
   595	| `positional` | positive integer | No | Optional 1-based CLI positional input slot. Values must be unique and contiguous starting at `1`. |
   596	| `validate` | string | No | Rust `regex`-crate pattern, matched against the fully rendered value. |
   597	
   598	## File Extension
   599	
   600	Template manifest files use the `.yaml` extension. Template plan entry points are exactly `plan.rhei.md` or `index.rhei.md`. In directory-workspace templates, files under `tasks/` may use `.md` consistent with standard Rhei workspaces.
   601	
   602	## Related Specifications
   603	
   604	- [Plan Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md) — Grammar and semantics of the output format
   605	- [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) — State machine format (bundled in templates)
   606	- [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) — Deterministic program execution (program states work in templates)
   607	- [How Rhei Is Used](rhei-usage.spec.md) — Roles and coordination patterns

 succeeded in 389ms:
     1	# Rhei Completion UX Specification
     2	
     3	Generate shell completion scripts for the `rhei` CLI. The command writes the script to stdout so users can either source it in the current shell or install it into their shell's normal completion directory.
     4	
     5	The generated scripts are dynamic: the shell calls back into the installed
     6	`rhei` binary at completion time. This keeps completions in sync with the
     7	current working directory, including discovered template names for
     8	`rhei instantiate <TEMPLATE>` and template-specific input arguments.
     9	
    10	## UX Goal
    11	
    12	Every meaningful command-line slot should complete. A user should be able to
    13	start with `rhei <TAB>` and discover the command tree, then keep pressing
    14	`<TAB>` through required positionals, option values, template inputs, task ids,
    15	state names, shell names, agent names, and filesystem paths without consulting
    16	documentation.
    17	
    18	Completions are advisory and must never change command semantics. If completion
    19	cannot load dynamic context, the CLI still runs normally and static completions
    20	continue to work.
    21	
    22	## Usage
    23	
    24	```bash
    25	rhei completions <SHELL>
    26	rhei completions <SHELL> --install
    27	rhei completions <SHELL> --install --system
    28	rhei completions <SHELL> --install --output <PATH>
    29	rhei completions bash
    30	rhei completions zsh
    31	rhei completions fish
    32	rhei completions powershell
    33	rhei completions elvish
    34	```
    35	
    36	## Arguments
    37	
    38	| Argument | Description |
    39	|----------|-------------|
    40	| `<SHELL>` | Target shell. Supported values: `bash`, `zsh`, `fish`, `powershell`, `elvish` |
    41	
    42	## Options
    43	
    44	| Flag | Default | Description |
    45	|------|---------|-------------|
    46	| `--install` | | Write the generated completion script to the shell's normal completion location instead of stdout |
    47	| `--user` | user | Install into the current user's shell configuration directories |
    48	| `--system` | | Install into system-wide completion directories, intended for package manager post-install scripts |
    49	| `--output <PATH>` | | Write to an explicit path instead of the default user or system path |
    50	| `--dry-run` | | Print the destination path without writing files |
    51	
    52	## Supported Shells
    53	
    54	Rhei supports the notable interactive shells covered by `clap_complete`:
    55	
    56	| Shell | Value | User install path | System install path |
    57	|-------|-------|-------------------|---------------------|
    58	| Bash | `bash` | `${XDG_DATA_HOME:-~/.local/share}/bash-completion/completions/rhei` | `/usr/local/share/bash-completion/completions/rhei` |
    59	| Zsh | `zsh` | `~/.zfunc/_rhei` | `/usr/local/share/zsh/site-functions/_rhei` |
    60	| Fish | `fish` | `${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/fish/completions/rhei.fish` | `/usr/local/share/fish/vendor_completions.d/rhei.fish` |
    61	| PowerShell | `powershell` | `${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/powershell/rhei-completions.ps1` | `/usr/local/share/powershell/Completions/rhei-completions.ps1` |
    62	| Elvish | `elvish` | `${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/elvish/lib/rhei-completions.elv` | `/usr/local/share/elvish/lib/rhei-completions.elv` |
    63	
    64	## Output Contract
    65	
    66	- The command prints only the completion script to stdout.
    67	- Diagnostics and parse errors are written to stderr through the normal CLI error path.
    68	- Unless `--install` or `--output` is passed, the command does not create, modify, or remove files.
    69	- With `--install`, the command creates parent directories as needed, overwrites the target completion file atomically enough for normal CLI use, and prints the installed path to stdout.
    70	- Generated completions call back into the current binary through the `COMPLETE` environment variable and reflect the current binary's command tree, global options, subcommands, flags, value enums, and supported dynamic argument values.
    71	- `rhei instantiate <TEMPLATE>` completes discovered project and user template names using the same precedence as `rhei templates`: `<project>/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/` first, then `~/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/`. If the partially typed value is path-like (absolute, dot-prefixed, or contains `/`), directory completion is used instead.
    72	
    73	## Completion Contract
    74	
    75	Completion is part of the CLI UX, not a best-effort extra. The generated scripts
    76	must expose the same completion behavior across Bash, Zsh, Fish, PowerShell, and
    77	Elvish as far as each shell's completion model permits.
    78	
    79	### Global Rules
    80	
    81	- Complete subcommands at every command position.
    82	- Complete every flag and option, including global flags such as
    83	  `--state-machine`.
    84	- Complete every value enum from the same source of truth as argument parsing.
    85	- Complete every filesystem path argument with a kind-specific path completer.
    86	- Complete dynamic values from local project state when enough prior arguments
    87	  are available to resolve them.
    88	- Filter candidates by the current token prefix.
    89	- Preserve user-typed quoting and escaping through the shell completion engine.
    90	- Do not print human diagnostics to stdout during dynamic completion.
    91	- Do not write files, acquire task locks, run callbacks, spawn agents, spawn
    92	  programs, or mutate metadata during completion.
    93	- Degrade quietly. If a plan, workspace, state machine, settings file, or
    94	  template manifest cannot be read, return the best static/path completions that
    95	  remain valid.
    96	
    97	### Candidate Display
    98	
    99	When the shell supports descriptions, candidates should include concise help:
   100	
   101	| Candidate | Help content |
   102	|-----------|--------------|
   103	| Subcommand | The command summary from the CLI definition |
   104	| Flag / option | The option help from the CLI definition |
   105	| Template | Template description and source (`project` or `user`) |
   106	| Template input key | Type, required/default status, positional index when present, and description |
   107	| Task id | Task title and current state |
   108	| State name | State description when available |
   109	| Assignee | Number of matching tasks when available |
   110	| Node kind | Number of matching tasks when available |
   111	| Agent / mode / model | Resolved provider/config description when available |
   112	| Filesystem path | Shell-native path display |
   113	
   114	Required values should sort before optional values. Values in the project
   115	should sort before values from user/global configuration. Already supplied
   116	non-repeatable values should be hidden unless the current token is editing that
   117	same value.
   118	
   119	### Filesystem Values
   120	
   121	Filesystem completion should match the argument's domain:
   122	
   123	| Argument | Completion behavior |
   124	|----------|---------------------|
   125	| `RHEI_PLAN` | Complete `.rhei.md` files and workspace directories containing `index.rhei.md`; plain directories remain traversable |
   126	| `--state-machine` | Complete `.yaml` and `.yml` files; directories remain traversable |
   127	| `--values` | Complete `.yaml`, `.yml`, and `.json` files; directories remain traversable |
   128	| `--output` | Complete directories and allow new leaf paths |
   129	| `completions --output` | Complete files and allow new leaf paths |
   130	| `--set-file KEY=PATH` | Complete files after the `=`; directories remain traversable |
   131	| Template `type: path` values | Complete files and directories after the input key or positional slot |
   132	| `reset RHEI_PLAN` | Complete `.rhei.md` files and workspace directories |
   133	
   134	Path-like template references are completed as directories. A template reference
   135	is path-like when it is absolute, dot-prefixed, or contains `/`.
   136	
   137	### Dynamic Context
   138	
   139	Dynamic completion may inspect only local files and configuration:
   140	
   141	- The current working directory and its `.agents/rhei/` tree.
   142	- User Rhei configuration under the documented user config directories.
   143	- The plan/workspace argument already present on the command line.
   144	- The selected template's `template.yaml`.
   145	- The selected or auto-discovered state machine.
   146	
   147	Completion must not use the network. It must not execute template output,
   148	program states, state callbacks, or agent commands.
