    97	**Format:** Plain markdown with Kilocode's frontmatter if supported, otherwise raw content.
    98	
    99	### Pi (`pi`)
   100	
   101	| Mode | Skill files |
   102	|------|-------------|
   103	| Global | `~/.pi/rules/rhei-<skill>.md` |
   104	| Local | `.pi/rules/rhei-<skill>.md` (project root) |
   105	
   106	**Format:** Plain markdown rule files. Pi loads all `.md` files from its rules directory as system context.
   107	
   108	### OpenAI Codex (`codex`)
   109	
   110	| Mode | Skill files | Registration |
   111	|------|-------------|--------------|
   112	| Global | `~/.agents/skills/rhei-<skill>/SKILL.md` | None |
   113	| Local | `.agents/skills/rhei-<skill>/SKILL.md` (project root) | None |
   114	
   115	**Format:** A standard Codex skill directory containing `SKILL.md` and any optional supporting files (`scripts/`, `references/`, `assets/`, `agents/`).
   116	
   117	**Note:** Codex discovers skills by scanning `.agents/skills` from the current working directory up to the repository root, plus `$HOME/.agents/skills` for user-level skills. No registration or marker injection file is needed. Custom spawned agents are configured separately under `.codex/agents/*.toml` or `~/.codex/agents/*.toml`; they inherit the parent session's available skills unless `skills.config` is explicitly overridden.
   118	
   119	### Google Antigravity (`antigravity`)
   120	
   121	| Mode | Skill files |
   122	|------|-------------|
   123	| Global | `~/.antigravity/rules/rhei-<skill>.md` |
   124	| Local | `.antigravity/rules/rhei-<skill>.md` (project root) |
   125	
   126	**Format:** Plain markdown rule files.
   127	
   128	## Behavior
   129	
   130	### Local installation
   131	
   132	With `--local`, skills are installed into the current project directory instead of the user's home directory. The command resolves the project root by walking up from the current directory to find a `.git` directory, `Cargo.toml`, `package.json`, or similar project marker. If no project root is found, it falls back to the current working directory.
   133	
   134	Local installation is useful for:
   135	
   136	- Sharing skills with collaborators via version control (the default copies files).
   137	- Scoping skills to a specific project without polluting the global config.
   138	- Overriding global skills with project-specific versions.
   139	
   140	When `--local` is combined with `--link`, the symlinks use relative paths so the project stays portable. Files installed with `--local` and `--link` should be added to `.gitignore` unless the intent is to commit them.
   141	
   142	### Detect installed skills
   143	
   144	Before writing, remove or replace any existing rhei skill files for the target agent and install the requested set again. Re-running `install-skills` refreshes previously installed skills in place instead of skipping.
   145	
   146	### Resolve skill source
   147	
   148	The command finds skill files relative to the `rhei` binary (e.g., `../share/rhei/skills/` for installed binaries, or `skills/` in the repo for dev builds).
   149	
   150	### Symlink vs copy
   151	
   152	The default behavior copies skill files into the target directory. `--link` symlinks instead — useful during development so skills stay up-to-date with local changes, but requires the rhei source to remain at a stable path.
   153	
   154	### Registration
   155	
   156	For agents that require explicit registration (Claude Code's `CLAUDE.md`), the command appends a delimited section. It uses markers (`<!-- rhei:start -->` / `<!-- rhei:end -->` or an `# rhei` heading) so uninstall and updates can find and replace the block idempotently.
   157	
   158	### Dry run
   159	
   160	With `--dry-run`, print each action (symlink, copy, append) without executing.
   161	
   162	### Uninstall
   163	
   164	With `--uninstall`, remove symlinks/copied files and delete the registered section from agent config files.
   165	
   166	## Example Output
   167	
